# =============================================================================
# pyret — Brown University's Pyret programming language compiler
#          + runner.  Pyret is a Python-and-Racket-derived
#          PEDAGOGICAL PROGRAMMING LANGUAGE designed at Brown's
#          PLT (Programming Languages and Tools) group by Shriram
#          Krishnamurthi (with key contributions from Joe Politz,
#          Justin Pombrio, Daniel Patterson, et al.) as the
#          successor to "How to Design Programs"-pedagogy Racket
#          (the Felleisen / Findler / Flatt / Krishnamurthi
#          textbook curriculum).  Pyret targets:
#            - Introductory programming courses (CS1/CS2)
#            - High-school computing education (Bootstrap algebra/
#              physics curricula at bootstrapworld.org)
#            - Teaching pre-college math via programming
#          Pyret distinguishing pedagogical design:
#            - Inferred types BUT with type annotations OPTIONAL
#              (gradual typing — start without types, add when
#              ready)
#            - First-class CHECK BLOCKS (`check "test name": ... end`)
#              — every Pyret function should have a check block
#              alongside it, executed automatically
#            - DATA declarations for algebraic data types with
#              automatic structural equality + visitor patterns
#            - Pattern matching via `cases` expressions
#            - Functional programming first (list operations,
#              higher-order functions, recursion)
#            - Spreadsheet-style TABLE primitives for data analysis
#              (`load-table`, `table.filter`, `table.transform`)
#            - WORLD module for graphical programming with image-
#              based animation (`big-bang`)
#          Used by hundreds of universities + thousands of high
#          schools through the Bootstrap curriculum (one of the
#          largest computing-education programs in the world).
#
# Author:  Brown University PLT Group (Shriram Krishnamurthi, Joe
#          Politz, Justin Pombrio, et al.) — Pyret development
#          started in 2010 as a graduate-research project; first
#          public release 2014.  Bootstrap curriculum (Emmanuel
#          Schanzer's pedagogical extension) brought Pyret to
#          K-12 education from 2014 onwards.
# Source:  https://github.com/brownplt/pyret-lang (main repo;
#          1126+ stars) + https://github.com/brownplt/pyret-npm
#          (the npm CLI wrapper that publishes the `pyret` binary)
# CLI:     pyret-npm/pyret.js (Node.js wrapper that invokes the
#                                Pyret compiler jar; uses
#                                75lb/command-line-args + 75lb/
#                                command-line-usage for argv
#                                parsing + help-text generation)
# Library: 75lb/command-line-args + 75lb/command-line-usage
#          (Lloyd Brookes / 75lb's Node.js argv parsing library
#           pair — `command-line-args` for parsing, `command-line-
#           usage` for rendering tagged-template help text with
#           {bold} / {underline} / {italic} inline markup.
#           Used by Pyret-npm, several Node.js documentation
#           generators, and the jsdoc family of tools.)
# License: Apache-2.0 (Pyret) + MIT (command-line-args)
# Status:  Active — 1126+ stars on brownplt/pyret-lang; pyret-npm
#          is the publishing CLI; command-line-args is 1059+ stars
#          on 75lb/command-line-args (continuous development since
#          2014 by Lloyd Brookes).
